{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"b13e4c6a-e4c2-4f3a-9bba-ef87de430c22","content":"Here's the skip attribute for each framework:\n\n**MSTest**\n```csharp\n[Ignore(\"Reason for skipping\")]\n```\n\n**xUnit**\n```csharp\n[Fact(Skip = \"Reason for skipping\")]\n// or for theories:\n[Theory(Skip = \"Reason for skipping\")]\n```\n\n**NUnit**\n```csharp\n[Ignore(\"Reason for skipping\")]\n```\n\n**TUnit**\n```csharp\n[Skip(\"Reason for skipping\")]\n```\n\nAll four will mark the test as \"skipped\" in results rather than hiding it entirely, so you'll still see it reported during test runs.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"b9cd630b-85cb-48fd-bf81-f6d59a943283","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about the correct attribute syntax to skip tests with a reason message in each of the four .NET test frameworks: MSTest, xUnit, NUnit, and TUnit. This is a straightforward knowledge question about .NET test frameworks. Let me provide the answer directly.","outputTokens":231,"requestId":"BD00:E210B:1F504B9:22FA2C0:6A07C4BD"},"id":"d34572be-12de-4899-82c0-fc889451630b","timestamp":"2026-05-16T01:13:40.038Z","parentId":"88567783-3e82-4039-a157-e0129d2de377"}
